- Initialize a lower bound lo to 1 and an upper bound hi to the maximum possible long value.
- Enter a loop that continues until the lower bound is greater than or equal to the upper bound.
- In each iteration of the loop, calculate the midpoint between the lower and upper bounds using the formula mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2.
- Calculate the number of completed trips that can be made in the mid time using a for loop that iterates over each time in the time array.
- If the number of completed trips is greater than or equal to the total number of trips required, update the upper bound hi to the mid value.
- Otherwise, update the lower bound lo to the mid value plus one.
- Repeat steps 3 to 6 until the lower bound is greater than or equal to the upper bound.
- Return the lower bound, which represents the minimum time required to complete the given number of trips based on the times in the array.
```
class Solution {
    public long minimumTime(int[] time, int totalTrips) {
    long lo = 1;
    long hi = Long.MAX_VALUE;

    while (lo < hi) {
        long mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;
        long completedTrips=0;
        for (int t : time) {
            completedTrips += mid / t;
            if (completedTrips >= totalTrips) break;
        }
        if (completedTrips>=totalTrips) {
            hi = mid;
        } else {
            lo = mid + 1;
        }
    }
    return lo;
    }
}
```
