solutions.content:
# Approach
Best approach is to play around with brute force solution and find out how can I tell how many trips can all busses take in time t. 
From this I can consider my t somewhere between 1 and 10^7 * totalTrips (worst case scenario). From this I can tell at index i if my time t lies before or after it, 
because if I can do totalTrips in time t, it means I can do totalTrips in every number after t. 
Same applies to case when I can't do totalTrips in t, then I can't do it before t.

This means I can find it in log(10^7*k) * n - because it costs n in worst case to determine max number of trips at time t.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(log(10^7*k)*n)$$ - it is better to scale up maximum to prevent large array iteration, because it costs only a few operation to cut it out in binary search.

- Space complexity:
$$O(1)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public long minimumTime(int[] time, int totalTrips) {
        long low = 1;
        long high = 10000000L * totalTrips;

        while (low < high) {
            long mid = (low+high)/2;

            if (!canComplete(mid, time, totalTrips)) {
                low = mid+1;
            } else {
                high = mid;
            }
        }

        return low;
    }

    private boolean canComplete (long t, int[] time, int totalTrips) {
        long sum = 0;
        for (int item: time) {
            sum += t / item;
            if (sum >= totalTrips) return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
}
```

